    <h2 class="cs-section-title">five phases over two years</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="cs-phases">
    <div></div>
    <div class="cs-phase-list">

      <div class="cs-phase">
        <div class="cs-phase-label">Phase 01 · 2023</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-title">Laying the foundation — Sitter Insights</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-body">
          We launched the Sitter Insights dashboard with metrics like response rate, booking rate, calendar updates, and cancellations. The experiment showed small but positive improvements in conversation booking rate, and more importantly, <strong>established a mental model</strong>: "this is where I understand how my business is doing." I joined as the project moved into development, refining details so the shipped experience could serve as the foundation for Star Sitter.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cs-phase">
        <div class="cs-phase-label">Phase 02</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-title">Star Sitter Beta — proving the badge</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-body">
          With the data foundation in place, we introduced Star Sitter in a limited set of markets. Provider-level, non-tiered status. Qualification based on bookings, response rate, star rating, new client booking rate, and repeat clients. <strong>Badge surfacing on search cards and profiles</strong>, plus a "Only show Star Sitters" filter. A static landing page explaining criteria and perks. The owner-side split test showed the badge meaningfully shifted behaviour and revenue — more conversations going to Star Sitters, higher conversion, higher average booking values.
        </div>

        <div class="cs-img-placeholder">
          <div class="mock-ui">
            <div class="mock-row accent"></div>
            <div class="mock-row med"></div>
            <div class="mock-row short"></div>
            <div style="height:1px;background:rgba(255,255,255,0.06);margin:4px 0;"></div>
            <div class="mock-row"></div>
            <div class="mock-row accent"></div>
            <div class="mock-row short"></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-img-caption">Star Sitter badge on search cards and profile pages</div>
      </div>

      <div class="cs-phase">
        <div class="cs-phase-label">Phase 03</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-title">Making it understandable — landing page and tracking</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-body">
          Early CX and social sentiment surfaced cracks: sitters struggling to understand booking rate, confusion about why "great" sitters lacked the badge, pain around edge cases. We iterated on two surfaces. On the landing page, quick usability tests showed sitters skimmed past key rules. We tightened copy to use direct, instructive phrasing and added a prominent "Check your progress" CTA. On the tracking side, we redesigned the Sitter Insights tab with <strong>a clearer status message, tiered "Learn more" patterns, and a real distinction between past snapshots and current-period metrics</strong>.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cs-phase">
        <div class="cs-phase-label">Phase 04</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-title">Making it fair — criteria, legacying, metric transparency</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-body">
          As the program scaled, fairness and explainability became as important as raw impact. We made three major changes. First, from lifetime to recent activity — 5 recent clients and 2 repeat clients in the last 6 months, so status reflects <em>currently</em> active, high-quality supply. Second, productized legacying: sitters who miss one metric can keep the badge for one grace period while remaining active. Third, we fixed the <strong>Contact More Sitters bias</strong> — excluding low-intent backup requests from the new client booking rate denominator, which moved a cohort of long-tenured sitters over the 33% threshold without lowering the bar for weaker supply.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="cs-phase">
        <div class="cs-phase-label">Phase 05 · Apr 2025</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-title">Scale and automate — rolling status</div>
        <div class="cs-phase-body">
          Quarterly refreshes gave us stability at launch, but created predictable CX spikes, a fragile batch process, and status that drifted out of sync with seasonality. We moved to a rolling model: <strong>sitters earn Star Sitter as soon as they meet the criteria</strong>; dropping below puts them into a three-month grace period; Trust &amp; Safety and diversion remain immediate disqualifiers. Notifications shift from quarterly blasts to contextual messaging. On the design side, this meant dramatically simplifying Sitter Insights — no more qualification period dropdowns, a single real-time picture of where sitters stand.
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</div>

