<!-- LEARNINGS -->
<div class="cs-body-section">
  <div class="cs-section-header">
    <div class="cs-section-num">04 — Learnings</div>
    <h2 class="cs-section-title">what I took away</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="cs-content">
    <div></div>
    <div>
      <div class="cs-learnings">
        <div class="cs-learning">
          <div class="cs-learning-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="cs-learning-title">A badge alone is not a program</div>
            <div class="cs-learning-body">Star Sitter began as a single badge, but the design challenge was really to create a living, explainable system that balances sitter motivation, owner trust, operational reality, and marketplace health. That lens drove every iteration.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-learning">
          <div class="cs-learning-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="cs-learning-title">Explainability is a product feature</div>
            <div class="cs-learning-body">The criteria themselves were sound — but sitters couldn't act on them if they couldn't understand them. Usability testing on the landing page and tracking tab unlocked more behaviour change than further metric tuning would have.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-learning">
          <div class="cs-learning-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="cs-learning-title">Fairness at scale requires constant maintenance</div>
            <div class="cs-learning-body">Edge cases like Contact More Sitters showed up only once the program was in production. Designing status programs means committing to ongoing fairness work — not just a launch spec.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="cs-learning">
          <div class="cs-learning-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="cs-learning-title">Batch logic creates predictable fragility</div>
            <div class="cs-learning-body">Quarterly refreshes felt safe but created engineering overhead, CX spikes, and sitter frustration. The move to rolling status reduced all three — and made the program feel more like a real business tool and less like a seasonal event.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

